00:00:49.682 --> 00:00:52.719
for NASA astrophysics, right.

00:00:52.719 --> 00:00:55.922
There are three paths that
we can take to get us there,

00:00:55.922 --> 00:00:58.757
to find evidence of
life beyond Earth.

00:00:58.757 --> 00:01:02.228
One is solar system exploration.

00:01:02.228 --> 00:01:06.432
This beautiful image of
the plumes of Enceladus,

00:01:06.432 --> 00:01:11.371
the landscapes of Mars
the Curiosity shows us,

00:01:11.371 --> 00:01:14.940
compels us
to explore the solar system

00:01:14.940 --> 00:01:16.475
and see if there is life lurking

00:01:16.475 --> 00:01:18.711
in any of these
nooks and crannies,

00:01:18.711 --> 00:01:22.748
in a subterranean cave on
Mars, in a subsurface ocean

00:01:22.748 --> 00:01:25.418
on Europa or Enceladus.

00:01:25.418 --> 00:01:27.320
Whether or not we find life?

00:01:27.320 --> 00:01:31.357
Maybe we'll find death,
in fossils, in extinction.

00:01:31.357 --> 00:01:35.495
Regardless, the
implications are profound.

00:01:35.495 --> 00:01:39.332 line:0%
The second path is
the SETI search,

00:01:39.332 --> 00:01:42.968 line:0%
ears to the universe, listening,
searching for signals that

00:01:42.968 --> 00:01:45.705 line:0%
are not astronomical
as we understand them.

00:01:45.705 --> 00:01:49.542 line:0%
Signals that are big
surprises that might be due to

00:01:49.542 --> 00:01:53.546
technology, might be due to
intelligent life depicted by

00:01:53.546 --> 00:01:57.717
the Allen Telescope Array
up in Northern California.

00:01:57.717 --> 00:02:00.119
But there's a third path

00:02:00.119 --> 00:02:06.024
and that's looking for the
cradles of life as we know it,

00:02:06.024 --> 00:02:10.129
looking for planets like Earth

00:02:10.129 --> 00:02:13.699
that could harbor surface
liquid water and could give rise

00:02:13.699 --> 00:02:16.101
to life as we understand
it here on Earth,

00:02:16.101 --> 00:02:18.271
carbon-based life.

00:02:18.271 --> 00:02:22.442
Well, this path was made
possible 20 years ago with

00:02:22.442 --> 00:02:25.845
the first discovery of an
exoplanet orbiting a normal

00:02:25.845 --> 00:02:28.781
main sequence kind
of star like our Sun,

00:02:28.781 --> 00:02:31.350
and I just happened to be
at that conference,

00:02:31.350 --> 00:02:33.653
I was a young graduate
student at the time,

00:02:33.653 --> 00:02:36.389
and it was a conference
on stars, not planets,

00:02:36.389 --> 00:02:39.158
that field of study
didn't exist at all!

00:02:39.158 --> 00:02:41.995
It was cool stars, stellar
systems and the Sun,

00:02:41.995 --> 00:02:44.831
no exoplanet in
the title, right?

00:02:44.831 --> 00:02:48.100
In fact, that talk
wasn't even on the agenda.

00:02:48.100 --> 00:02:51.537
But next thing we knew, Michel
Mayor, a Swiss astronomer,

00:02:51.537 --> 00:02:54.140
went up to the stage,
cameras were there,

00:02:54.140 --> 00:02:59.145
and announced the
discovery of 51 Peg b,

00:02:59.145 --> 00:03:03.182
and it blew our mind!

00:03:03.182 --> 00:03:06.452
It was unlike anything
we understood, right?

00:03:06.452 --> 00:03:09.322
We understood the solar
system; close to the star

00:03:09.322 --> 00:03:12.124
you've got the small rocky
planets; further out,

00:03:12.124 --> 00:03:14.894
you've got the ice
and gas giants, right?

00:03:14.894 --> 00:03:17.063
That's how solar systems
are supposed to form,

00:03:17.063 --> 00:03:18.764
that's how they're supposed
to lay out, our own

00:03:18.764 --> 00:03:21.000
solar system says it is so.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:23.469
And yet, here we had
a planet discovery,

00:03:23.469 --> 00:03:26.539
a planet almost as
large as Jupiter,

00:03:26.539 --> 00:03:29.942
with a four-day orbital
period around its star,

00:03:29.942 --> 00:03:32.979
blasted by stellar radiation.

00:03:32.979 --> 00:03:37.984
Theorists did not know how
to make a planet like that.

00:03:37.984 --> 00:03:40.720
And that's basically how
the field of exoplanets

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:43.288
has been ever since.

00:03:43.288 --> 00:03:44.423
We have uncovered

00:03:44.423 --> 00:03:48.160
an unparalleled
diversity of worlds.

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:51.564
But what we want to look for,
what NASA wants to look for

00:03:51.564 --> 00:03:55.968
are worlds not like this
gas giant

00:03:55.968 --> 00:03:58.104
blasted by stellar irradiation

00:03:58.104 --> 00:04:00.273
where surface
liquid water cannot exist;

00:04:00.273 --> 00:04:02.741
we're looking for
the cradles of life.

00:04:02.741 --> 00:04:06.479
And so we fast forward
to March of 2009.

