Through this technique
of transit photometry,

00:08:22.301 --> 00:08:26.672 line:0%
measuring brightness,
Kepler has found over 4,200

00:08:26.672 --> 00:08:31.310 line:0%
transiting objects; 90
percent of which, or more,

00:08:31.310 --> 00:08:35.347 line:0%
are going to be bona fide
exoplanets, planets orbiting

00:08:35.347 --> 00:08:37.416
other stars in our galaxy.

00:08:37.416 --> 00:08:41.687
Our blinders have been
lifted to small planets.

00:08:41.687 --> 00:08:44.857
The landscape has changed
dramatically, right?

00:08:44.857 --> 00:08:47.660
Now more than 85 percent of
the known planets

00:08:47.660 --> 00:08:49.161
or the planets
known to humanity,

00:08:49.161 --> 00:08:52.631
are smaller than Neptune,
instead of larger,

00:08:52.631 --> 00:08:53.999
which just goes to show

00:08:53.999 --> 00:08:57.102
that our technology, we were
hampered by our technology.

00:08:57.102 --> 00:09:00.472
Every time you build a
new piece of technology,

00:09:00.472 --> 00:09:02.908
you learn a tremendous amount.

00:09:02.908 --> 00:09:05.911
Moreover, you can see that
there are some yellow points

00:09:05.911 --> 00:09:10.415
kissing that Earth locus
at one Earth diameter

00:09:10.415 --> 00:09:13.519
and 365-day orbital periods.

00:09:13.519 --> 00:09:18.190
So Kepler has begun to find
Earth, true Earth analogues.

00:09:19.825 --> 00:09:24.363
The big question that
Kepler set out to answer is,

00:09:24.363 --> 00:09:28.734
"What fraction of stars in
our galaxy harbor

00:09:28.734 --> 00:09:31.036
potentially habitable
Earth-sized planets?"

00:09:31.036 --> 00:09:35.141
We want to get a feeling for
the for the ubiquity of planets

00:09:35.141 --> 00:09:37.209
like Earth, these
cradles of life,

00:09:37.209 --> 00:09:39.144
these potential cradles of life.

00:09:39.144 --> 00:09:40.580
Are Earths common?

00:09:41.646 --> 00:09:43.649
Are they are they prevalent
in our galaxy

00:09:43.649 --> 00:09:47.119
or is our own Earth
somehow special?

00:09:47.119 --> 00:09:49.154
So what have we
learned from Kepler?

00:09:49.154 --> 00:09:52.157
From Kepler, we can now with
this large sample of planets,

00:09:52.157 --> 00:09:56.361
we can ask the question, "Okay,
what is the population of

00:09:56.361 --> 00:09:58.730
planets out there?
What is their diversity?

00:09:58.730 --> 00:10:01.166
What is the population?

00:10:01.166 --> 00:10:04.803
How far do I have to go
out into the galaxy before I

00:10:04.803 --> 00:10:09.508
happen upon a potentially
habitable Earth-sized planet?"

00:10:09.508 --> 00:10:12.010
You can ask this question
because of Kepler.

00:10:12.010 --> 00:10:16.649
And so the answer is, if we
were to take our own galaxy

00:10:16.649 --> 00:10:19.417
and we were to shrink it down
to the size of the continental

00:10:19.417 --> 00:10:22.488
United States, and you
stand on one coast,

00:10:22.488 --> 00:10:25.124
maybe here in Washington,
D.C., you look out

00:10:25.124 --> 00:10:28.627
over the continent and
you ask yourself,
"How far is the nearest

00:10:28.627 --> 00:10:31.363
potentially habitable
Earth-sized planet?"

00:10:31.363 --> 00:10:36.602
The answer is, about a stroll
across the National Mall,

00:10:36.602 --> 00:10:38.137
between about
the Capitol building

00:10:38.137 --> 00:10:40.005
and the Lincoln Memorial,

00:10:40.005 --> 00:10:42.541
or about 15 light years.

00:10:42.541 --> 00:10:45.644
( audience laughter )

00:10:45.644 --> 00:10:49.715
Which is very close, given
the fact that the galaxy is

00:10:49.715 --> 00:10:52.451
100,000 light-years across.

00:10:52.451 --> 00:10:54.486
( continued chuckles )

00:10:54.486 --> 00:10:56.856
Okay, so what's next?

00:10:56.856 --> 00:11:00.225
So we're kind of learning
that Earth-like planets are

00:11:00.225 --> 00:11:02.294
pretty common; that's good.

00:11:02.294 --> 00:11:05.931
That means that exploration,
finding evidence of life,

00:11:05.931 --> 00:11:08.367
following this path,
has great potential.

00:11:08.367 --> 00:11:10.135
So, what's next?

00:11:10.135 --> 00:11:13.238
Well here on the left, I'm
showing you an image actually

00:11:13.238 --> 00:11:16.875
taken of Venus
transiting our own Sun.

00:11:16.875 --> 00:11:20.612
This is an actual image of a
planet in our own solar system

00:11:20.612 --> 00:11:23.648
transiting across
the surface of our Sun.

00:11:23.648 --> 00:11:26.351
The Hinode spacecraft
took this image,

00:11:26.351 --> 00:11:30.389
and I'm showing it to you
because I want you to see

00:11:30.389 --> 00:11:35.394
the very thin layer of orange
hugging that planet.

00:11:35.394 --> 00:11:37.062
Do you see that?

00:11:37.062 --> 00:11:40.032
That's the Venusian atmosphere.

00:11:40.032 --> 00:11:43.402
It's very thin; it's only
five kilometers thick.

00:11:43.402 --> 00:11:46.739
I think that's about the scale
height we call it, very thin.

00:11:46.739 --> 00:11:49.040
In terms of area, if you
collected that whole area,

00:11:49.040 --> 00:11:54.212
it's only 1/200 the
area of the disc itself.

00:11:54.212 --> 00:11:59.584
So it's very, very thin, but
here's the thing: the sunlight,

00:11:59.584 --> 00:12:04.289
shining on the planet from
behind is filtering

00:12:04.289 --> 00:12:07.359
through that atmosphere
that's hugging it.

00:12:07.359 --> 00:12:10.696
And when it does that, the
atmosphere itself is leaving

00:12:10.696 --> 00:12:13.031
a fingerprint on that light.

00:12:13.031 --> 00:12:15.234
If I'm on the other side,
I can collect that light,

00:12:15.234 --> 00:12:19.171
I can spread it out
into a spectrum, I inspect it,

00:12:19.171 --> 00:12:22.107
and I can disentangle

00:12:22.107 --> 00:12:24.176
the fingerprint
that that atmosphere left

00:12:24.176 --> 00:12:25.810
on the light.

00:12:25.810 --> 00:12:30.249
Which means, I may have the
ability with enough sensitivity

00:12:30.249 --> 00:12:34.053
to disentangle what that
atmosphere was made of.

00:12:34.053 --> 00:12:39.492
On the right-hand side of
this image is cyanobacteria,

00:12:39.492 --> 00:12:43.028
it's like algae, and this
microscopic picture of

00:12:43.028 --> 00:12:48.633
cyanobacteria was caught
in the act of metabolizing

00:12:48.633 --> 00:12:52.871
and producing
a tiny burp of oxygen;

00:12:52.871 --> 00:12:57.976
the very process which created
the oxygen on our own planet

00:12:57.976 --> 00:13:01.113
and gave rise
to more complex life forms.

00:13:01.113 --> 00:13:04.049
So, that's the kind of signature
that we would want to see

00:13:04.049 --> 00:13:07.018
by catching the light filtering
through the atmosphere.

00:13:07.018 --> 00:13:09.488
That's called "transmission".

00:13:09.488 --> 00:13:12.691
Now that's very tough, but
the James Webb Space Telescope

00:13:12.691 --> 00:13:16.595
is going to do that very thing
for maybe larger planets,

00:13:16.595 --> 00:13:18.931
more like mini-Neptunes.

00:13:18.931 --> 00:13:24.770
Another technique that I'm
looking forward to is imaging.

00:13:24.770 --> 00:13:27.939
What we really want,
talking about big dreams,

00:13:27.939 --> 00:13:31.543
what we really want is to catch
the light reflecting off

00:13:31.543 --> 00:13:33.611
of the surface of a planet.

00:13:33.611 --> 00:13:36.181 line:0%
Here you've got the
Blue Marble on the left,

00:13:36.181 --> 00:13:39.951 line:0%
an iconic image taken by the
Apollo astronauts leaving Earth

00:13:39.951 --> 00:13:41.519 line:0%
on the way to the moon.

00:13:41.519 --> 00:13:45.590 line:0%
That's an image that was
taken from 22,000 miles away;

00:13:45.590 --> 00:13:48.460 line:0%
the first full disk
image of our planet.

00:13:48.460 --> 00:13:52.163 line:0%
And you can see the reflected
light, the light from the Sun

00:13:52.163 --> 00:13:54.800 line:0%
that's reflecting off the
planet and into the camera

00:13:54.800 --> 00:13:57.169 line:0%
of the Apollo astronaut.

00:13:57.169 --> 00:14:01.606 line:0%
On the right-hand side, it's
the pale blue dot of Earth,

00:14:01.606 --> 00:14:07.545 line:0%
taken by the Cassini spacecraft
from 900 million miles away.

00:14:07.545 --> 00:14:11.416
It's unresolved; you don't
see the surface features,

00:14:11.416 --> 00:14:13.685
